metadata.name: odium #33
metadata.description:
The idea behind "odium" is to mix the two previous works to create a new art, which maintains similarities with the previous projects, but also with its differences and peculiarities.

"odium" is based on an algorithm that I've been exploring since the "radium" and "illusions" projects. So this is the last of the series.

It is composed by with grainy/noise and flowfields, creating a glitch effect as it is finishing to render.
"odium" have random colormaps instead a configured palette system, patterns of growth and plays with randomized blendModes and colorModes, 
and I name it "odium"  because the form it grows and glitch reminds me how the hate sometimes slowly consume the mind.

This is a project made in p5.js


Omar Lobato, 04/29/2022.

metadata.name: Connected #3
metadata.description:
An artistic version of the travelling salesperson problem.
In this particle system, each particle has to visit a complete set of attractors.
The path of each particle is then plotted, resulting in unique abstract geometries.


Artist: Estienne
Made with p5.js
Dec 2021

metadata.name: Bamboo #34
metadata.description:
During my childhood we had a small patch of bamboo in our backyard. 
I fondly remember playing with the hollow sticks but also cutting myself on the fibrous leaves.
"Bamboo" aims to capture the adventures I would envision while looking at that small jungle in my garden.

Inspiration was drawn from pointillism, botanical illustration and naive art.

The piece is purely generative, in the sense of painting the picture with code via p5js points and shapes, no assets are used.

Generative parameters include density of elements, parameters of elements and color. 

Thank you so much for collecting!

's' to capture a 6400 x 6400 png with border

'b' to capture a 6400 x 6400 png without border

metadata.name: ELEMENTS #25
metadata.description:
This series began with a technique I did not know before (generative stitching) and which produced results I did not like at first. In a way, the ELEMENTS series really started after this, when I had something I did not like, but wanted to produce something interested with. The path is sometimes better than the destination.

It's easy to explore ideas we like, it's a lot harden when we don't.
